06771nam a22009255i 9783110757668DE-B159720230502090707.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230502t20212022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831107576687 a10.1515/97831107576682doi  a(DE-B1597)589177  a(OCoLC)1291507276  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aART0280002bisacsh04a701.0300aRhapsodic Objects :bArt, Agency, and Materiality (1700-2000) /ced. by Noemie Etienne, Yaelle Biro. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (236 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContact Zones : Studies in Global Art ,x2196-3746 ;v700tFrontmatter -- tContent -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1: Interlaced Patterns -- tWandering Designs -- tThe Art of Printed Textiles -- tChintzes as Printed Matter and Their Entanglement within the Transatlantic Slave Trade around 1800 -- tPart 2: Embedded Relationships -- tInterpretations of Central African Taste in European Trade Cloth of the 1890s -- tThe Picturesque in Peking -- tCultural Intersections and Identity in Algeria on the Eve of the French Invasion -- tPart 3: Crafted Identities -- t"What Is Colonial Art? And How Can It Be Modern?" -- tCrafting Colonial Power -- tA World of Knowledge -- tFrida Kahlo's Circulating Crafts -- tAuthors -- tPicture Credits0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aCirculation and imitation are key factors in shaping the material world. The authors in this volume explore how technical knowledge, immaterial desires, and political agendas impact the production and consumption of visual and material culture across times and places. Their essays map multidirectional transactions for cultural goods in which source countries can be positioned at the center. Rhapsodic - literally to stitch or weave songs - paired with objects - from thrown against - intertwines complexity and action. Rhapsodic objects thus beckons to the layered narratives of the objects themselves, their making, and their reception over time. The concept further underlines their potential to express creativity, generate emotion, and reveal histories - often tainted with violence.  aZirkulation und Nachahmung haben einen wesentlichen Einfluss auf die Gestaltung der materiellen Welt. Die Beiträge des Bandes untersuchen, wie technisches Wissen, immaterielle Wünsche und politische Agenden die Produktion und Rezeption der visuellen und materiellen Kultur im Wandel der Zeit und Orte prägten. Sie gehen den Wanderungen von Kulturgütern unter besonderer Berücksichtigung ihrer Entstehungskontexte nach. Mit dem Begriff des "rhapsodischen Objektes" werden dabei die vielschichtigen, nicht immer in einem Zusammenhang stehenden Erzählungen der Objekte angesprochen.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Schweizerischer Nationalfonds (SNF)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 4aKulturtransfer. 4aKunsthandwerk. 4aObjekte. 4aTextilien. 7aART / Techniques / General.2bisacsh  aObjects.  aarts and crafts.  acultural transfer.  atextile.1 aArmstrong, Dorothy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiro, Yaelle, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBiro, Yaëlle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEtienne, Noemie, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGlaister, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGril-Mariotte, Aziza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.go